Loading data

library("dplyr")
library("stringr")
library("ggplot2")

# Data from reddit user austingwalters in this reddit thread: https://www.reddit.com/r/udub/comments/4e6kxl/i_made_a_website_that_shows_grade_distributions/
# Dataset and FOIA info from their dropbox: https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fo/8lbyazjlt5jmv86jvvs06/AGtgMaWeyZtZuS2fSYLYn_4?dl=0&e=1&rlkey=1sg7t372nhslxogwjl3e9lt9t

uw_grades_original_df <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kylethayer/Info-201-au-24-datasets/refs/heads/main/UW-Seattle_20110-20161-Course-Grade-Data_2016-04-06.csv", check.names=FALSE)
 
# From Course_Number get program abbreviation (Program_Abv) and number (Course_Number_Num)
# From Term get Term_Season
uw_grades_df <- uw_grades_original_df |> 
  mutate(
    Program_Abv = str_split_i(Course_Number, " ", 1),
    Course_Number_Num = as.integer(str_extract(Course_Number, "\\d+")),
    Term_Season = str_extract(Term, "Autumn|Spring|Summer|Winter")
  )

Overall grade distribution summary

course_count <- uw_grades_df |> nrow()
average_average_GPA <- round(uw_grades_df |> pull(Average_GPA) |> mean(na.rm = TRUE), 2)
average_students <- round(uw_grades_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> mean(na.rm = TRUE), 2)
min_course_num <- uw_grades_df |> pull(Course_Number_Num) |> min()
max_course_num <- uw_grades_df |> pull(Course_Number_Num) |> max()
  1. There are a total of 39242 courses in the data set.
  2. The average GPA across all the courses is 3.41.
  3. The average number of students in courses is 45.38.
  4. The lowest number for a course number is 100.
  5. The highest number for a course number is 750.
ggplot(uw_grades_df, aes(x = Average_GPA)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of average GPA in UW courses",
       x = "Average GPA",
       y = "Count")
ggplot(data = uw_grades_df) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Student_Count, y = Average_GPA)) +
  labs(title = "Student counts and average GPAs in UW classes",
       x = "Student count",
       y = "Average GPA")

Data observations

A total of 39242 courses at UW holds an average of 45.38 students and a 3.41 GPA per class for all courses in the data set. The range of levels for course numbers have a minimum of 100 and a maximum of 750. Looking at the data from the first graph, we cans see the distribution of average course GPAs and we can tell that there is a peak right around 3.5. This means that the average of all average GPAs across all courses in the data set fall around 3.5, which we know to be true from our data earlier. The second graph shows us an interesting phenomenon where classes between an average GPA of 2.5-3.6 span a large range of student counts between 0 to around 700 students. Only about 1 or 2 courses seem to break this trend, disregarding these classes, anything that falls outside of the previously stated GPA range tends to have much lower student counts, hardly ever reaching 300 and never going above 400.

Comparisons #1: Computer Science and Communications

CSE_df <- uw_grades_df |> filter(Program_Abv == "CSE")
COM_df <- uw_grades_df |> filter(Program_Abv == "COM")

# CSE data
CSE_total_student_count <- CSE_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> sum()
CSE_avg_avg_GPA <- round(CSE_df |> pull(Average_GPA) |> mean(), 2)
CSE_avg_student_count <- round(CSE_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> mean(), 2)
CSE_max_course_number_num <- CSE_df |> pull(Course_Number_Num) |> max()

# COM data
COM_total_student_count <- COM_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> sum()
COM_avg_avg_GPA <- round(COM_df |> pull(Average_GPA) |> mean(), 2)
COM_avg_student_count <- round(COM_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> mean(), 2)
COM_max_course_number_num <- COM_df |> pull(Course_Number_Num) |> max()

Graphing

# CSE course number num vs average GPA scatterplot
ggplot(data = CSE_df) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Course_Number_Num, y = Average_GPA)) +
  labs(title = "Computer science course number num vs average course GPA",
       x = "Course number num",
       y = "Average GPA")
# COM course number num vs average GPA scatterplot
ggplot(data = COM_df) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Course_Number_Num, y = Average_GPA)) +

       x = "Course number num",
       y = "Average GPA")
# CSE average GPA distribution
ggplot(CSE_df, aes(x = Average_GPA)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1) +
  labs(title = "Average CSE GPA distribution",
       x = "Average GPA",
       y = "Count")
# COM average GPA distribution
ggplot(COM_df, aes(x = Average_GPA)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1) +
  labs(title = "Average COM GPA distribution",
       x = "Average GPA",
       y = "Count")

Comparison summary

Looking at the average of the average GPAs across all courses in the data set for each program, we can see that computer science has an average of a 3.43 and communication has an average of a 3.36 GPA. Computer science on average has larger class sizes, with an average of 77.68 students compared to communicationâs 45.96 average students per class. We can also see that the computer science program has more students overall with 51737 students across all CSE classes in the data set compared to communicationâs 38560 students. Both have a large number of students but the computer science department is larger. The highest course number num that the computer science and communication programs reach is 599 and 597 respectively. Looking at the first set of graphs, we can immediately notice that the computer science program appears not to have any 200 level courses. Computer science courses appear to have a higher average GPA as the course number num increases, whereas communication courses seem to have a consistent pattern of average GPAs in 100-400 level courses and then 500 level courses have a higher average GPA. Moving to the second set of graphs, while communicationâs GPA distribution seems to have an almost normal distribution with a slight left skew and a peak around 3.4, computer scienceâs GPA distribution is heavily skewed left and has two peaks, a smaller one at 2.7 and the primary peak at 3.7.

Comparisons #2: Andrew Loveless and Kyrzyztof Burdzy

loveless_df <- uw_grades_df |> filter(Primary_Instructor == "LOVELESS, ANDREW")
burdzy_df <- uw_grades_df |> filter(Primary_Instructor == "BURDZY, KRZYSZTOF")

# Loveless data
loveless_avg_avg_GPA <- round(loveless_df |> pull(Average_GPA) |> mean(), 2)
loveless_avg_student_count <-
  round(loveless_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> mean(), 2)
loveless_max_student_count <- loveless_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> max()
loveless_max_course_number_num <-
  loveless_df |> pull(Course_Number_Num) |> max()

# Burdzy data
burdzy_avg_avg_GPA <- round(burdzy_df |> pull(Average_GPA) |> mean(), 2)
burdzy_avg_student_count <- round(burdzy_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> mean(), 2)
burdzy_max_student_count <- burdzy_df |> pull(Student_Count) |> max()
burdzy_max_course_number_num <- burdzy_df |> pull(Course_Number_Num) |> max()

Graphing

# Loveless course number num vs average GPA scatterplot
ggplot(data = loveless_df) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Course_Number_Num, y = Average_GPA)) +
  labs(title = "Loveless course number num vs average GPA",
       x = "Course number num",
       y = "Average GPA") +
  ylim(0, 4)
# Burdzy course number num vs average GPA scatterplot
ggplot(data = burdzy_df) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Course_Number_Num, y = Average_GPA)) +
  labs(title = "Burdzy course number num vs average GPA",
       x = "Course number num",
       y = "Average GPA") +
  ylim(0, 4)
# Create new datasets to graph
loveless_MATH_125_df <- loveless_df |>
  filter(grepl("MATH 125", Course_Number, fixed = TRUE))
loveless_125_GPA_by_term_df <- loveless_MATH_125_df |>
  group_by(Term) |>
  summarize(Term_Average_GPA = mean(Average_GPA))
loveless_125_GPA_by_term_df <- loveless_125_GPA_by_term_df |>
  mutate(Term = str_extract(Term, "\\(.*\\)"), Term = str_sub(Term, 2, -2))

burdzy_MATH_125_df <- burdzy_df |>
  filter(grepl("MATH 125", Course_Number, fixed = TRUE))
burdzy_125_GPA_by_term_df <- burdzy_MATH_125_df |>
  group_by(Term) |>
  summarize(Term_Average_GPA = mean(Average_GPA))
burdzy_125_GPA_by_term_df <- burdzy_125_GPA_by_term_df |>
  mutate(Term = str_extract(Term, "\\(.*\\)"), Term = str_sub(Term, 2, -2))

# Loveless MATH 125 average GPA by term bar chart
ggplot(data = loveless_125_GPA_by_term_df) +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = Term, y = Term_Average_GPA)) +
  labs(title = "Loveless MATH 125 average GPA by term",
       y = "Term average GPA") +
  ylim(0,4)
# Burdzy MATH 125 average GPA by term bar chart
ggplot(data = burdzy_125_GPA_by_term_df) +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = Term, y = Term_Average_GPA)) +
  labs(title = "Burdzy MATH 125 average GPA by term",
       y = "Term average GPA") +
  ylim(0,4)

Comparison summary

Looking at the average GPAs between both instructors, we can see that Loveless has a higher average GPA of 3.03 than Burdzy does with an average of 2.78. However it is important to take into account that Burdzy teaches higher level classes up to level 492 than Loveless does whose highest level course is 324 which might account for disparity in course difficulty. This might also account for the fact that Loveless has a higher average number of students per course than Burdzy with 112.06 and 71.54 students respectively. The largest course in terms of student count that Loveless teaches is 198 which is larger than Burdzyâs 128 max students. Looking at the first graph, if we focus just on the 100 level courses, we can see that the Average GPA for Lovelessâs courses has a number of points significantly higher than Burdzyâs courses ever reach meaning that in 100 level courses students likely tend to achieve higher GPAs than in Burdzyâs courses. The second graph dives into a specific 100 level course that both instructors teach which is MATH 125. Comparing these two graphs we can see that Loveless has a consistently higher average GPA than Burdzy in this course. While Lovelessâs courses often have an average GPA over 3.0, all of Burdzyâs courses remain below this mark.
